-- Definition -- A code list with values indicating the status of the act of the observation.
-- Description -- This is an empty code list serving as a super-class for a number of specific code lists which can specify the MO_ObservationStatusValue values. In MOLES the ISO 19115 MD_ProgressCode code list is used.

-- Definition -- A specialisation of OM_Observation class.
-- Description -- SOURCE [ ISO 19156:2011] An instance of MO_Observation exists in support of a project which requires this observation to accomplish its objectives.
-- Definition -- A free text description of the observation including its intentions.
-- Definition -- Reference to documentation describing the observation.

-- Definition -- Description of the geographic area , e.g. bounding polygon, within which the observation's result is available.
-- Description -- GeographicExtent is the envelope of the geographic areas of multiple coverages.

-- Definition -- External identifier of the observation.
-- Description -- NOTE The identifier may be used by an external application to reference an observation. EXAMPLE An identifier can be used for packaging an observation to an observation collection.

-- Definition -- Restrictions on the access and use of observation's result.
-- Desription -- Restrictions on the access and use of the observation result are known without navigating from the obseravtion to the result.
-- Definition -- Publication state of observation metadata record.
-- Definition -- Individual or organisation related to observation.
-- Definition -- Narrative description of the result's domain density ( temporal and/or spatial resolution and/or spectral) .

-- Definition -- Frequency with which additions are/were made to the observation's result.
-- Description -- EXAMPLE Measurements of rain rate at Chilbolton Observatoty,UK are being conducted since 2000. This is an onGoing observation with a result being growing on a daily basis.

-- Definition -- Status of the act of the observation.
-- Description -- EXAMPLE Measurements of rain rate at Chilbolton Observatoty,UK are being conducted since 2000. The status of this observation is onGoing.
NOTE If an observation is onGoing then the relative Project shall be onGoing.

-- Definition -- Information about the vertical extent of the Observation's result.
-- Description -- verticalExtent is the envelope of the vertical extents of multiple coverages.

-- Definition -- Observable property consisting of two or more simple observable properties.

  • constraint>ObservablePropertyConstraint.label>Daily maximum

MOLES model follows the ISO 19115-2 pattern but introduces its own concepts of instrument platform and platform operation. It seems that the MOLES pattern is a generalisation of ISO 19115-2 pattern. -- Definition -- A platform is an identifiable object which can either i)bring the acquisition instrument(s) to the appropriate environment (e.g aircraft, ground station); ii) create the appropriate environment for the acquisition instrument(s) ( e.g a cloud chamber) ; or iii) provide the appropriate operational conditions to the instruments (e.g a ground station provides electricity ) in order to acquire the data according to the observation objectives.
-- Description -- NOTE A platform may be a member of a complex of parent and child platforms.

-- Definition -- An identifiable activity designed to accomplish a set of objectives. -- Description -- A typical sequence of data capturing involves one or more projects for which a number of observations are conducted, using appropriate tools and methods, to produce data sets. EXAMPLE 1 The UK Surface Ocean /Lower Atmosphere Study (UK SOLAS) was a Directed Mode programme of the Natural Environment Research Council (NERC). The overall aim of UK SOLAS was to advance understanding of environmentally significant interactions between the atmosphere and ocean, focusing on material exchanges that involve ocean productivity, atmospheric composition and climate. NOTE 1 A project may be a member of a complex of parent and child-projects. NOTE 2 A project contributes to zero or more Observation collections.
